1. models.py (The Database Blueprint)

    This file is usually created first. It acts as the blueprint for the database,
    defining exactly what kind of information the application will store.

    Libraries Imported:

    models from django.db: This allows the application to use Django's built-in
                        database tools to create tables without writing raw SQL code.

    User from django.contrib.auth.models: This brings in the system's user accounts so that a food
                                          item can be linked to the specific person (or chef) who created it.

    Contents and Classes:

    MEAL_TYPE and STATUS Variables: These are lists of predefined choices.
                                    MEAL_TYPE categorizes food into starters, salads, main dishes, and desserts.
                                    STATUS acts as an on/off switch to mark an item as "Unavailable" (0) or "Available" (1).

    class Item(models.Model): This creates a database table called "Item" to store individual food dishes.
                            It defines fields for the dish's name (meal), a text description, the cost (price),
                            the category (meal_type), the creator (author), and whether it is currently available (status).
                            It also automatically records the dates the item was created and last updated.

    def __str__(self): This is a helper function. It tells the system that whenever it needs to display an
                        Item object as text (like in the admin dashboard), it should just show the name of the
                        meal (e.g., "Pizza") instead of a confusing database ID (e.g., "Item Object (1)").

2. admin.py (The Management Dashboard)

    After creating the database structure, this file is used to register the newly created
    model so that the site administrator can manage the data through a user-friendly website dashboard.

    Libraries Imported:

    admin from django.contrib: This imports Django's built-in admin panel tools.

    Item from .models: This imports the specific food blueprint created in the first step.

    Contents and Classes:

    class MenuItemAdmin(admin.ModelAdmin): This class customizes how the food items are displayed in the admin dashboard.

    list_display tells the dashboard to show both the meal's name and its availability status in the main list.

    list_filter creates a sidebar allowing the admin to easily filter items to see only "Available" or "Unavailable" dishes.

    search_fields adds a search bar at the top so the admin can quickly find a dish by typing its name or description.

    admin.site.register(...): This command officially connects the Item model and the custom MenuItemAdmin
                                settings to the admin dashboard.

3. views.py (The Logic and Data Fetcher)

    Once the database is set up and manageable, the system needs logic to fetch data from
    the database and send it to the web pages (HTML templates) that the user sees.

    Libraries Imported:

    generic from django.views: This imports pre-written, standard "views" (logic templates) that save time,
                                such as displaying a list of items or details of one item.

    Item and MEAL_TYPE from .models: This allows the logic to interact with the database and the predefined
                                    food categories.

    Contents and Classes:

    class MenuList(generic.ListView): This logic handles the homepage.
                                      It is designed to grab a list of all food items from the database, organize them
                                      by the date they were created, and send that data to a file called index.html.
                                      It also sends the MEAL_TYPE list so the webpage can group the foods by category.


    class MenuItemDetail(generic.DetailView): This handles the page for a single, specific food dish. It takes one
                                            Item from the database and sends it to the menu_item_detail.html file to
                                            be displayed.

    class About(generic.ListView): This logic is responsible for rendering the "About" page, linking the user to
                                    the about.html file.

4. restaurant_menu/urls.py (The App's Navigation Map)

    After the logic (views) is written, the application needs to know which web address (URL) should
    trigger which piece of logic. This file acts as a localized map for the restaurant menu app.

    Libraries Imported:

    path from django.urls: This tool is used to define individual URL routes.

    views from .: This imports all the logic classes created in the previous step so they can be attached to URLs.

    Contents:

    urlpatterns: This is a list that connects web addresses to the views.

    path('') connects the base address (the homepage) to the MenuList view.

    path('item/<int:pk>') connects an address with a specific ID number (like /item/5) to
    the MenuItemDetail view, ensuring the system pulls up the correct food item.

    path('about/') connects the /about/ web address to the About view.

5. mysite/urls.py (The Project's Master Map)

    This is the master navigation file for the entire website. It tells the main project where to
    route general internet traffic.

    Libraries Imported:

    admin from django.contrib: This allows the master map to route traffic to the admin dashboard.

    path and include from django.urls: path defines the route, and include allows this master
                                        map to forward traffic to the smaller, localized maps
                                        (like the one created in step 4).

    Contents:

    urlpatterns: This is the master list of all website routes.

    path('admin/') ensures that anyone typing /admin into their browser is directed to the management dashboard.

    path('', include('restaurant_menu.urls')) takes any traffic going to the main,
    empty web address (the homepage) and forwards it entirely to the restaurant_menu app's
    map so that the app can handle the routing from there.